(Lexxi)</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukrazakthule.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Krazak Thule</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 317<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/7/02 1:11:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2498.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Recommendations</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Druid</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
This is what I would choose. Yes, Shaman and Cleric are both good too, but I'd choose Druid, and here's why. <br>
<br>
(a) Your friend is a human paladin, and I believe the only place they can start is Freeport. If Queynos is an option though, that would be good. <br>
<br>
Humans cannot be shaman, however. Only Vah Shir, Ogres, Trolls, and Barbarians can be shaman. Paladins are as &quot;good&quot; (lawful) as they come. You don't want to be an evil Ogre or Troll shaman teamed with a Paladin. Likewise, you don't want to be a Vah Shir, because you'll have to travel too far to hook up. At lower levels, too dangerous. Barbarian shaman start in Halas, and it's a ways for them to travel to Freeport. <br>
<br>
(b) As a druid, you can be human, which would put you in close proximity to your friend (if he starts in the same city as you). Or you can choose half-elf, or wood-elf. If I recall correctly, human and half-elf druids start in Surefall Glade, near Queynos. Wood elf druids start in Kelethin. It's relatively easy to get to Freeport from Kelethin, especially if you can get a SoW for crossing Butcher Block Mountains. <br>
<br>
Surefall Glade is close to Queynos. If your friend starts in Freeport (which again I am sure all Paladins do) then getting a ride to the Freeport area isn't tough, from where you start. There are druid rings right inside Surefall Glade, and you should be able to get a SoW and port to Commons. <br>
<br>
(3) Druids make great partners. They can heal, and so can a paladin, so between the two of you, healing should be covered pretty fair. They can also SoW, so you can run away from trouble. They get damage shields, which should never be overlookedin combat. And their DoT's will help your paladin friend take down the enemy that much faster. <br>
<br>
(4) Druids can port. This might not sound like a big deal now, but later it will be. Travel in EQ can be a pain, and if the two of you like to travel around, explore, and try different zones for hunting, having your druid will be a huge asset. <br>
<br>
(5) Druids can track. Shaman can't. This can be important later for quests, when  you need to get the named spawn of some creature to get the item you need. Paladins have quite a few quests too, I believe. A druid tracker would be helpful. <br>
<br>
(6) Druids can Snare. This is important fighting certain mobs, especially in dungeons. <br>
<br>
(7) Both of you can root-park for crowd control. <br>
<br>
Really, druid-paladin is an ideal pairing. You basically have nearly every single tool necessary at your disposal to play and enjoy this game. <br>
<br>
